{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3584649,"name":"","username":"Cade","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/c/fbc32d/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-04-09T01:00:32.174Z","cooked":"

My team was going to try to make our own custom PCBs that would work like the SWYFT CANnect Wiring System to clean up the wiring, reduce port usage on our mini power module and make our CAN bus more reliable. If you are not familiar with the SWYFT CANnect it allows you to run CAN bus and 12V Power over standard Ethernet cables. An ethernet cable has 8 wires in it which would allow us to run both CAN and 12V twice in parallel for redundancy. My question is would running 2 sets of CAN cause interference or some other problem or would it work.

You should be fine so long as you use the correct pins, you’ll want both CAN1H and CAN1L to be on a twisted pair, and CAN2H and CAN2L to be on a separate twisted pair. I’d think so long as the PCB traces are relatively short you wouldn’t have problems, but I’ll let somebody more versed in PCB signal integrity comment on that

Make sure you follow the FRC standard for passive PoE pin locations. I don’t know which pins they are, could probably ring it out with a multimeter on a radio power module or Poe injector cable.

Signal integrity on the PCB will not be an issue, CAN is fairly robust.
